Statistics with FPL

R is a popular programming language for statistical analysis and visualisation. To make the most of R, packages that contain different functions to manipulate data can be installed.

For this project, we need to load several packages. If a package isnt installed, you can install it using install.packages().

# Load packages
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(cowplot)
library(geomtextpath)
library(lessR)
library(BSDA)

1. Getting Data

A first step is to set a working directory, so you know where any output files are saved. We can then read in data directly from a GitHub repository that contains historical data from the Premier League.

# Set wd
setwd('/Users/alicesmail/Desktop/Programming/Statistics/FPL')

# Data is from vaastav's repository
github <- 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vaastav/Fantasy-Premier-League/master/data/'

# We want details about GW1 from 2023-24
gw1 <- read_csv(url(paste0(github, "2023-24/gws/gw1.csv")))

2. Descriptive Statistics: How Many Players Are in Each Team?

First we are going to use dplyrs %>% operator to group players by team, and then count them using summarise(). We can then get the mean, standard deviation and quantiles of how many players are in each team. 

# Get team size
teamSize <- gw1 %>% group_by(Team=team) %>% summarise(N=n())

# Get mean & SD
teamSizeMean <- mean(teamSize$N)
teamSizeSD <- sd(teamSize$N)

# Get Q1, median & Q3
teamSizeQuantiles <- data.frame(n=quantile(teamSize$N, prob=c(0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1)))

# View
teamSizeMean
## [1] 32.9
teamSizeSD
## [1] 4.387782
teamSizeQuantiles
##          n
## 0%   25.00
## 25%  29.75
## 50%  33.00
## 75%  35.25
## 100% 42.00
We have identified the mean team size as 32.9, with a standard deviation of 4.39.

3. Visualisation: How Many Players Are in Each Team?

To visualise this information, we can use a bar chart to show how many players are in each team. 

# Set a theme to apply to all output graphs
theme <- theme_classic() + theme(text = element_text(size = 12, family='Franklin Gothic Book'))

# Set output size for plots
knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.width=5, fig.height=3) 
# Use ggplot to input values for x and y axis
ggplot(teamSize, aes(x=Team, y=N)) + 
  # Add type of graph (col)
  geom_col() + 
  # Add theme
  theme +
  # Rotate axis labels
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)) +
  # Add line indicating mean
  geom_texthline(label = 'Mean', yintercept = 32.9, family='Franklin Gothic Book')

We can also use a boxplot to represent the quartiles. 

# Copy dataframe, add a single variable to group all teams together, and turn into factor
teamSizeBox <- teamSize
teamSizeBox$`All Teams` <- 'All Teams'
teamSizeBox$`All Teams` <- as.factor(teamSizeBox$`All Teams`)

# Use ggplot to input values for x and y axis
ggplot(teamSizeBox, aes(y=N, x=`All Teams`)) + 
  # Add type of graph (boxplot)
  geom_boxplot() +
  # Add theme
  theme +
  # Remove axis label
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank())

4. The Normal Distribution: How Many Players Are in Each Team?

Because the team size for each club is likely to centre around the mean, it is probable that this data fits the normal distribution. We can quantify whether this is true using a QQ plot and the Shapiro-Wilks test. 

# Does data follow normal distribution: QQ plot
ggplot(teamSize, aes(sample=N)) + 
  geom_qq_line() +
  stat_qq() +
  theme_classic() + 
  theme + 
  labs(x='Theoretical Team Size', y='Actual Team Size')

From the QQ plot it appears that this data is normally distributed. 

# Does data follow normal distribution: Shapiro-Wilks
shapiro.test(teamSize$N)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  teamSize$N
## W = 0.97504, p-value = 0.8556

A non-significant result from the Shapiro-Wilks indicates normality. We can now plot a normal curve using the mean and SD values. 

# Plot values between Mean-4SD and Mean+4SD
ggplot(data = data.frame(x = c(teamSizeMean-4*teamSizeSD, 
                               teamSizeMean+4*teamSizeSD)), aes(x)) +
  # Add the normal distribution using our calculated mean and SD
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = teamSizeMean, sd = teamSizeSD)) + 
  # Add labels
  labs(y="Probability Density", x="Value") + 
  # Add theme
  theme

We can also add lines to indicate the mean and SD values. 

# Plot the curve as before
ggplot(data = data.frame(x = c(teamSizeMean-4*teamSizeSD, 
                               teamSizeMean+4*teamSizeSD)), aes(x)) +
  labs(y="Probability Density", x="Value") + 
  theme +
  # Add mean and SD lines
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(teamSizeMean,
                            teamSizeMean+1*teamSizeSD,
                            teamSizeMean+2*teamSizeSD,
                            teamSizeMean+3*teamSizeSD,
                            teamSizeMean-1*teamSizeSD, 
                            teamSizeMean-2*teamSizeSD, 
                            teamSizeMean-3*teamSizeSD), linetype='dashed', colour='grey')+
  # Add curve on top of lines
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = teamSizeMean, sd = teamSizeSD))

To understand what the normal distribution is showing, we can add blocks to demonstrate the 68-95-99.7 rule, where approximately 68% of the data falls within 1SD of the mean, 95% of the data is within 2SD, and 99.7% of the data is within 3SD. 

# Plot the curve as before
ggplot(data = data.frame(x = c(teamSizeMean-4*teamSizeSD, 
                               teamSizeMean+4*teamSizeSD)), aes(x)) +
  labs(y="Probability Density", x="Value") + 
  theme +
  # Fill curve between SDs
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = teamSizeMean, sd = teamSizeSD),
                xlim=c(teamSizeMean-3*teamSizeSD, teamSizeMean+3*teamSizeSD),
                geom = "area", aes(fill='99.7%')) +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = teamSizeMean, sd = teamSizeSD),
                xlim=c(teamSizeMean-2*teamSizeSD, teamSizeMean+2*teamSizeSD),
                geom = "area", aes(fill='95%')) +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = teamSizeMean, sd = teamSizeSD),
                xlim=c(teamSizeMean-1*teamSizeSD, teamSizeMean+1*teamSizeSD),
                geom = "area", aes(fill='68%')) +
  scale_fill_manual("Percentage", values = c('#73a5c2', '#a4d6b3', '#e2e882')) +
  # Add curve on top of colour blocks
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = teamSizeMean, sd = teamSizeSD))

Now we can see if there are any extreme values that differ a lot from this distribution. We can normalise the value for each team to obtain a z-score, and identify any outliers, which are typically defined as having a value above Mean+3SD or below Mean-3SD. 

# Get z-scores for each team
teamSize$zscore <- (teamSize$N - teamSizeMean)/teamSizeSD

# Get team with the highest z-score
teamSize %>% arrange(-abs(zscore)) %>% head(n=1) %>% as.data.frame()
##            Team  N   zscore
## 1 Nott'm Forest 42 2.073941

No teams are outliers, but the most extreme value is Nottm Forest, which has a team size of 42. We can add this value to the normal curve. 

# Plot the curve as before
ggplot(data = data.frame(x = c(teamSizeMean-4*teamSizeSD, 
                               teamSizeMean+4*teamSizeSD)), aes(x)) +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = teamSizeMean, sd = teamSizeSD)) + 
  labs(y='Probability Density', x='Count') + 
  theme + 
  # Add line and label for Nott'm Forest
  geom_textvline(label = "Nott'm Forest", 
                 xintercept = 42, 
                 colour='#f05022', family='Franklin Gothic Book')

5. Hypothesis Testing: Was the Mean Team Size Different in 2022-23?

We want to know if the mean team size in 2023-24 is significantly different to the mean team size from 2022-23 - this is the hypothesis that we are going to test.

To do this we can use a two-sample z-test, which can be used to compare the means of two different groups. A two-sample z-test has some assumptions that we first need to check for:
  • The data follows a normal distribution, or the sample size is larger than 30.
  • We know the variance for both groups.
First we will get data from GW1 for both seasons. 

# We want details about GW1 from 2022-23 and 2023-24
gw1_2022 <- read_csv(url(paste0(github, "2022-23/gws/gw1.csv")))
gw1_2023 <- read_csv(url(paste0(github, "2023-24/gws/gw1.csv")))

# Get team size for each dataset
teamSize_2022 <- gw1_2022 %>% group_by(Team=team) %>% summarise(N=n())
teamSize_2023 <- gw1_2023 %>% group_by(Team=team) %>% summarise(N=n())

# Get mean & SD for each dataset
data.frame(mean=c('2022'=mean(teamSize_2022$N),'2023'=mean(teamSize_2023$N)), 
           sd=c('2022'=sd(teamSize_2022$N), '2023'=sd(teamSize_2023$N)))
##       mean       sd
## 2022 28.65 2.134306
## 2023 32.90 4.387782

The mean team size for 2022-23 is lower than the mean team size for 2023-24. But is it significantly lower? We can test this using a z-test.

First we will investigate whether this is an appropriate test, and plot the two distributions to visualise their differences. 

# Combine both datasets together so we can plot both
teamSize_2022$Year <- '2022-23'
teamSize_2023$Year <- '2023-24'
teamSizeComb <- rbind(teamSize_2022, teamSize_2023)

# Does 2022-2023 data also follow normal distribution: QQ plot
ggplot(teamSizeComb, aes(sample=N, colour=Year)) + 
  geom_qq_line() +
  stat_qq() +
  theme_classic() + 
  theme + 
  labs(x='Theoretical Team Size', y='Actual Team Size')

# Does data follow normal distribution: Shapiro-Wilks
shapiro.test(teamSize_2022$N)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  teamSize_2022$N
## W = 0.939, p-value = 0.2295
shapiro.test(teamSize_2023$N)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  teamSize_2023$N
## W = 0.97504, p-value = 0.8556

Both datasets approximately follow a normal distribution. We can visualise the distribution of team sizes in both seasons using a violin plot. 

# Use ggplot to input values for x and y axis
ggplot(teamSizeComb, aes(y=N, x=Year)) + 
  geom_violin() +
  theme

We can see from a violin-plot that the distribution for each season is quite different. We can do a z-test to see if the means are significantly different.
  • We are using a z-test because both datasets are approximately normal. Typically the sample needs to be larger (n>30) for a z-test, but we already know our data is approximately normal.
  • We will use a two-sided test as our alternative hypothesis is that the mean for 2022-23 is significantly different from 2023-24. If we were hypothesising that is was significantly smaller OR larger we would use a one-sided test.
  • The null hypothesis is that the means are the same, so we are testing to see if we can confidently reject this hypothesis. 

# Get means and SD
teamSize_2022Mean <- mean(teamSize_2022$N)
teamSize_2023Mean <- mean(teamSize_2023$N)
teamSize_2022SD <- sd(teamSize_2022$N)
teamSize_2023SD <- sd(teamSize_2023$N)

# Calculating the z-score manually
zscore <- (28.65-32.90)/sqrt(teamSize_2023SD**2/20 + teamSize_2022SD**2/20)
print(paste('Z-score:', round(zscore, 4)))
## [1] "Z-score: -3.8953"
# Getting the p-value equivalent to this z-score
pval <- pnorm(q=zscore)

# We need to multiply this by two as we are performing a two-tailed test.
pval<-pval*2
print(paste('P-value:', round(pval, 6)))
## [1] "P-value: 0.000098"

To understand how these two figures relate to each other, we can plot the z-score on a standard normal curve.

The area under the curve between -Inf & -3.8953 and 3.8953 & Inf corresponds to the probability value (p-value) of getting that result or a more extreme result. 

# Plot a standard normal distribution
ggplot(data = data.frame(x = c(-5,5)), aes(x)) +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = 0, sd = 1)) +
  labs(y="Probability Density", x="Value", colour='Year') + 
  theme + 
  # Add our z-score
  geom_vline(xintercept=zscore, colour='#73a5c2') +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = 0, sd = 1),
              xlim=c(-5, zscore),
              geom = "area", aes(fill='0.00009807%'))+
  scale_fill_manual("Percentage", values = c('#73a5c2'))

Because the z-score is far from 0, we cannot see the area under the curve it corresponds to. Lets zoom in. 

# Plot the standard normal curve as before
ggplot(data = data.frame(x = c(-5,-3.5)), aes(x)) +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = 0, sd = 1)) +
  labs(y="Probability Density", x="Value", colour='Year') + 
  theme + 
  geom_vline(xintercept=zscore, colour='#73a5c2') +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = 0, sd = 1),
              xlim=c(-5, zscore),
              geom = "area", aes(fill='0.009807%'))+
  scale_fill_manual("Percentage", values = c('#73a5c2'))

So the probability of getting a zscore as or more extreme than -3.8953 or 3.8953 is 0.00009806812. This is much smaller than the standard p-value threshold of 0.05, meaning it is highly probable that the alternative hypothesis is true and we can reject the null hypothesis.

We can also perform this test using the z.test() function: 

# Calculating the z-score using the function z.test
z.test(teamSize_2022$N, teamSize_2023$N,
  alternative = "two.sided",
  sigma.x=teamSize_2022SD, sigma.y=teamSize_2023SD)
## 
##  Two-sample z-Test
## 
## data:  teamSize_2022$N and teamSize_2023$N
## z = -3.8953, p-value = 0.00009807
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -6.388423 -2.111577
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     28.65     32.90

From this test, we can conclude that the mean team size in 2022-23 was significantly smaller than the mean team size in 2023-24.
